entry.title: Winter Weather Advisory issued October 27 at 4:56AM AKDT until October 28 at 6:00AM AKDT by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Mixed precipitation, including freezing rain, snow, and rain expected. Total ice accumulations of a glaze to a few hundreths of an inch. Snow accumulations of up to 2 inches.
* WHERE...Bristol Bay from Dillingham north, including Koliganek and New Stuyahok.
* WHEN...From 7 PM Sunday to 6 AM AKDT Monday.
* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Precipitation is expected to begin Sunday evening as snow before transitioning to a period freezing rain Sunday night into early Monday morning. In general, precipitation is expected to turn to all rain Monday morning. There is still some uncertainty as to exactly when the transition from freezing rain to rain will occur. If cold air holds on longer, expect ice totals closer to a few hundrenths of an inch. Should temperatures warm faster, expect only a glaze of ice.

entry.title: Flood Watch issued October 27 at 2:29AM HST until October 27 at 6:00PM HST by NWS Honolulu HI
entry.summary:
...FLOOD WATCH FOR ALL HAWAIIAN ISLANDS THROUGH THIS AFTERNOON...
* WHAT...Flash flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be possible.
* WHERE...All the main Hawaiian islands.
* WHEN...Through this afternoon.
* IMPACTS...Flood prone roads and other low lying areas may be closed due to elevated runoff and overflowing streams. Urban areas may receive more significant flooding and property damage due to rapid runoff.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - An upper low will move over the islands today and result in continued unstable conditions within a very moist atmosphere. There will be enough instability to produce periodic showers. Rain could become locally heavy, with a chance for isolated thunderstorms, particularly over windward areas. Periods of heavy showers over already saturated grounds could quickly lead to runoff and flash flooding issues. Water levels in elevated streams could rise rapidly with additional heavy rain.

Snow will spread from west to east across the Lower Kuskokwim Valley starting Sunday evening and pick up in intensity Sunday night. Snow will become lighter from west to east Monday morning while moderate snow will persist for locations near the Western Alaska Range. There is some mixed precipitation/freezing rain potential across the western most areas of the region, including Aniak with warmer air trying to nudge in aloft. The best chance at a period of mixed precipitation for western areas would be Sunday evening before cooler air aloft works back in late Sunday night into Monday morning. In general, expect most snow to fall from Crooked Creek southeastward to Lime Village where 3 to 6 inches are possible. Higher amounts are likely near the Western Alaska Range.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 26 at 11:25AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
Confidence is increasing in a strong wind event for early next week. Model guidance continues to trend upwards in the potential for an impactful wind event with the next low pressure moving into the gulf for Monday into Tuesday.
The biggest challenge is how close does the low get to the outer coast. If the low is farther north and east, some of the strongest winds will be along the outer coast with gusts potentially reaching 50 to 60 mph with this solution. If the low remains farther to the south and west before weakening and moving inland, the strongest winds will remain offshore but places could still wind gusts above 40 mph along the outer coast.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 26 at 11:25AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
We continue to monitor the possibility of a significant snow event for portions of northern Panhandle beginning Monday night into Tuesday.
Cold air is still expected to move into the region during this weekend with increasing north winds across the panhandle. Early next week there is high confidence on a low moving into the Gulf of Alaska, spreading moisture and advecting warmer air over the colder airmass.
The main concern regarding this event will be how far east the low is as it moves into the Gulf. A track further north and east will allow moisture and warmer air to expand farther north, limiting snow amounts. Meanwhile, a track further south and west will limit how far north the moisture and warming spreads.
The biggest challenge is, when do winds switch from north and east to south and west. This switch would mix warmer air down to the surface allowing for a switch from snow to rain as well as limiting snow accumulations.
As always, the latest forecast information can be found at www.weather.gov/Juneau.
